<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-04-24T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-04-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="72" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1109: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-04-25T12:00:00+08:00">April 25,
                                1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 25—5:40
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>289. Legation’s 285, April 24, 3 p.m. Legation is telegraphing the
                            Minister for Foreign Affairs the substance of Canton’s April 24,
                                noon,<note n="97" xml:id="d72fn97">See telegram of even date from
                                the Consul General at Canton to the Secretary of State, <ref target="#pg_104">p. 104</ref>.</note> and is urging upon him the
                            importance of instructing the authorities in Kwangtung and Kiangsi to
                            cooperate in bringing relief to foreigners in southern Kiangsi.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>